The DOM (Document Object Model) represents an HTML page as a tree of objects so JavaScript can read and modify it. The browser creates this structure when it loads the page.
Example HTML:
                        <body>
                          <h1 id="title">Hello</h1>
                          <p class="text">Paragraph 1</p>
                          <p class="text">Paragraph 2</p>
                        </body>
JavaScript uses DOM methods to find elements in this tree.
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------

1. getElementById()
Selects one element by its id.
let heading = document.getElementById("title");
Returns one element
ID must be unique
Example:             heading.style.color = "red";


2. getElementsByClassName()
Selects all elements that have a specific class.
let items = document.getElementsByClassName("text");
Returns an HTMLCollection (array-like).
Example:       items[0].style.color = "blue";


3. getElementsByTagName()
Selects all elements with a specific HTML tag.
let paragraphs = document.getElementsByTagName("p");
Example:          paragraphs[1].style.fontWeight = "bold";
Also returns an HTMLCollection.


4. querySelector()
Selects the first element that matches a CSS selector.
let element = document.querySelector(".text");
Examples:
                                    document.querySelector("#title")   // by id
                                    document.querySelector(".text")    // by class
                                    document.querySelector("p")        // by tag


5. querySelectorAll()
Selects all elements matching a CSS selector.
let elements = document.querySelectorAll(".text");
Returns a NodeList.
Example:
                                  elements.forEach(el => {
                                    el.style.color = "green";
                                  });

Modern JavaScript mostly uses:
                                querySelector()
                                querySelectorAll()
because they work with CSS selectors, which are more flexible.
Example:   document.querySelector("div.container p.text")

